<h2>Elastos 2.0 Installation And Use</h2>
    <p>Elastos currently supports boot from GRUB.Introduction to GRUB functionality and characteristics:- 
    <h3>Elastos boot up through GRUB. What is GRUB?</h3>
        <p>GRUB is a multiple boot manager, which stands for GRand&nbsp;Unified&nbsp;Bootloader, developed by GNU group. GRUB implements important characteristics of bootloader: </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Complete command line and graphical interface support.</li>
            <li>Can recognize fdisk partition and BSD disk mark.</li>
            <li>Dynamically reads Linux&nbsp;ext2fs and ReiserFS, BSD&nbsp;ufs, MS-DOS&nbsp;FAT16 and FAT32, Minix file system and hardcode block table information.</li>
            <li>Can load Multiboot compatible operating system kernel (For example GNU&nbsp;Mach and Elastos) or standard Linux, *BSD kernel.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Elastos can boot through GRUB and can also boot from network or boot without disk through GRUB.</p>
        <p>This article describes the process of start Elastos through GRUB. For more details about GRUB please visit website: <a class="style1" href="http://www.gnu.org/software/grub/">http://www.gnu.org/software/grub/</a></p>
    <h3>Elastos supports multiple boot method.</h3>
        <p>With the support of GRUB, Elastos can support multiple boot methods.For details please see <a class="style1" href="../use_elastos.htm">installation and use of Elastos&nbsp;2.0</a>.</p>
        </ul>
        <p>About how to install and start Elastos operating system, please see <a class="style1" href="setup_elastos.htm">steps for install and start Elastos</a>.</p>
